---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import Breadcrumbs from '../components/Breadcrumbs.astro';
import DisclaimerBox from '../components/DisclaimerBox.astro';
import { SITE } from '../config';
import { AUTHOR } from '../data/author';
---
<BaseLayout
  title="About Honestly Profitable"
  description="Honestly Profitable was built by Daniel Hernandez, one person who got tired of business advice that was really just a sales pitch. Real startup costs, realistic earnings, and straight talk, with no courses to sell."
  path="/about"
>
  <div class="container container-narrow page-head">
    <Breadcrumbs items={[{ label: 'Home', href: '/' }, { label: 'About' }]} />
    <h1>About Honestly Profitable</h1>
    <p class="lead">The honest business reference I wish I had when I was trying to figure out what I could actually start.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="container container-narrow page-body">
    <div class="about-author">
      <span class="about-avatar" aria-hidden="true">
        <span class="about-initials">{AUTHOR.initials}</span>
        <img src={AUTHOR.photo} alt="Daniel Hernandez" width="112" height="112" decoding="async" onerror="this.remove()" />
      </span>
      <div class="about-author-meta">
        <p class="about-author-name">{AUTHOR.name}</p>
        <p class="about-author-role">Founder of {SITE.name}</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h2>Why I built this</h2>
    <p>
      I should be upfront about something. I am not a business guru, and I do not have a course to
      sell you. I am just the person who got frustrated enough with bad advice to build the site I
      wish had already existed.
    </p>
    <p>
      A few years ago I wanted to start something of my own. I did what everyone does. I searched, I
      watched videos, and I read article after article about the best businesses to start. Almost
      all of it was selling me something. A course, a coaching call, an affiliate link to a tool I
      did not need. The numbers were always the flattering ones. You would see the person who hit
      five figures in their first month, and never the twelve months most people quietly earn close
      to nothing.
    </p>
    <p>
      I got close to putting real money into an idea because a polished video made it look simple.
      When I finally sat down and did the math myself, counting the fees, the returns, the ad spend,
      and the hours, the whole thing came apart. It was not a business. It was a thumbnail.
    </p>
    <p>
      What I could not find anywhere was someone willing to just tell me the boring truth. What does
      it really cost. How long before you earn anything real. What are the honest odds. What goes
      wrong, and who it goes wrong for. So I started keeping my own notes. One spreadsheet turned
      into a folder of them, plain breakdowns of every model I looked into, written the way I wished
      someone had explained it to me.
    </p>
    <p>
      That folder is basically this website now. I kept noticing that other people were typing the
      same questions into Google and getting the same sales pitches I did. Honestly Profitable is my
      answer to that. It is the reference I needed and could not find, so I made it.
    </p>
    <p>
      I founded and launched Honestly Profitable, and I still set the standard for every page. The
      library has grown far beyond what one person can research alone, so the breakdowns are now
      produced and reviewed by our editorial team. That is why each article is credited to the
      Honestly Profitable Editorial Team rather than to me. The mission has not changed: honest
      numbers, real risks, and nothing to sell you.
    </p>

    <h2>What I promise you</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Real ranges, not best-case numbers.</strong> Beginner, experienced, and top-earner outcomes are kept separate, because blending them together is exactly how people get misled.</li>
      <li><strong>The hard parts come first.</strong> If a business is expensive, heavily regulated, or fails often, I say so plainly, right on the page, not in the fine print.</li>
      <li><strong>No courses, no upsells, no secret system.</strong> I have nothing to sell you, so I have no reason to hype anything.</li>
      <li><strong>If I would not say the number to a friend with a straight face,</strong> it does not go on the page.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>How our editorial team researches each business</h2>
    <p>
      Our editorial team builds every breakdown from public data, industry cost guides, government
      wage figures, and the accounts of people who actually run these businesses. We are not
      affiliated with any company, franchise, or tool mentioned here, and nobody pays to be included
      or described more kindly. You can read exactly how we work in
      <a href="/how-we-research-businesses">how we research businesses</a>,
      <a href="/data-sources">data sources</a>, and our <a href="/editorial-standards">editorial standards</a>.
    </p>

    <h2>How the site stays free</h2>
    <p>
      I want to be honest about the money too. This site is free, and advertising is what keeps it
      that way. {SITE.name} may show ads from networks such as Google AdSense. I keep them clearly
      labeled, well away from the cost and earnings figures, and never dressed up as a recommendation.
      Ads have no influence over which businesses I cover or what I say about them. See the
      <a href="/privacy-policy">privacy policy</a> for how advertising cookies work and how to opt out.
    </p>

    <h2>Editorial independence</h2>
    <p>
      My only real obligation is to the person reading a page and trying to make a genuine decision.
      No advertiser, and no business I write about, gets a say in the research or the numbers. That
      line is the entire point of the site, and I do not cross it.
    </p>

    <h2>Found something wrong? Tell me.</h2>
    <p>
      Accuracy is the whole job. If a number looks off or out of date, especially if you run one of
      these businesses yourself, I genuinely want to hear about it. Send it through the
      <a href="/contact">contact page</a> and I will look into it and fix the page if you are right.
      I would much rather be corrected than be wrong.
    </p>

    <div style="margin-top: 2rem;">
      <DisclaimerBox />
    </div>

    <p class="page-updated">Last updated: July 2026 · {SITE.domain}</p>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .about-author {
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    gap: 1.1rem;
    padding: 1.25rem 1.4rem;
    margin-bottom: 2rem;
    background: var(--surface);
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    border-left: 4px solid var(--green);
    border-radius: var(--radius);
  }
  .about-avatar {
    position: relative;
    display: grid;
    place-items: center;
    width: 72px;
    height: 72px;
    flex: none;
    border-radius: 50%;
    overflow: hidden;
    background: var(--navy);
    color: #fff;
    font-family: var(--font-display);
    font-weight: 800;
    font-size: 1.5rem;
  }
  :global(:root[data-theme='dark']) .about-avatar {
    background: var(--green-dark);
    color: #04120a;
  }
  .about-avatar img {
    position: absolute;
    inset: 0;
    width: 100%;
    height: 100%;
    object-fit: cover;
  }
  .about-author-name {
    font-family: var(--font-display);
    font-weight: 800;
    font-size: 1.2rem;
    color: var(--navy);
    margin: 0;
  }
  .about-author-role {
    color: var(--muted);
    margin: 0.15rem 0 0;
    font-size: 0.95rem;
  }
</style>
